WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.560
Today, Sean and I are going to be talking about R and Python, a data science love story

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:14.900
and why we're very excited to bring this news to you.

00:00:14.900 --> 00:00:20.820
So starting off, giving a bit of an overview, we'll be talking about why we're really excited

00:00:20.820 --> 00:00:26.879
to bring R and Python together in RStudio and provide it to the data science teams that

00:00:26.879 --> 00:00:29.180
we work with.

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:33.660
In this webinar specifically, what we're going to want to show you is how data scientists

00:00:33.660 --> 00:00:40.700
can use R and Python together on a single data science project, how DevOps and IT can

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:47.099
support this bilingual group of data scientists in their development efforts in a single development

00:00:47.099 --> 00:00:52.619
infrastructure, and how these bilingual data science teams can efficiently collaborate

00:00:52.619 --> 00:00:57.099
and share their work with their business stakeholders so that the insights that they generate can

00:00:57.099 --> 00:01:01.180
actually be used to make better data driven decisions.

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:06.139
We'll wrap up then talking a little bit about our ongoing community investment from RStudio

00:01:06.139 --> 00:01:09.099
in both the R and Python communities.

00:01:09.099 --> 00:01:13.940
And then we'll talk about how you can get more information on any of the points we discussed

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:18.379
today, as well as answer as many questions as we can.

00:01:18.379 --> 00:01:22.059
Next slide, please.

00:01:22.059 --> 00:01:30.339
So over the years, the focus of RStudio has been how do we help organizations really realize

00:01:30.339 --> 00:01:36.400
the full value of their data science investments, complementing the large investments in open

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:41.059
source data science that we've made at the beginning of our company.

00:01:41.059 --> 00:01:46.139
As part of that, it's been in our DNA to really focus on how do we integrate with all the

00:01:46.139 --> 00:01:51.699
tools and environments that data scientists need to use to do their work.

00:01:51.699 --> 00:01:56.540
Early on, we introduced Shiny, which is a way of building interactive web-based visual

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:59.540
applications using pure R code.

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:05.500
We also have done a lot of integration with Spark through our Sparkly R package.

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:10.960
And we've also done a lot of work to make it easier to access data, use SQL and integrate

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:11.960
with databases.

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:17.179
So all along, we've had this focus on integrating with all the tools that a data scientist might

00:02:17.179 --> 00:02:18.860
need.

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:22.619
In the last few years, as we've talked to our data science customers, we've seen that

00:02:22.619 --> 00:02:27.660
there are a lot of bilingual data science teams, a lot of teams that really need to

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:34.259
use both R and Python together in order to exploit the best of both environments.

00:02:34.259 --> 00:02:38.639
And so with the last couple of years, we've added a focus on integrating with various

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:41.539
capabilities on the Python side.

00:02:41.539 --> 00:02:46.339
That started off with integration with TensorFlow, which led to our development of the reticulate

00:02:46.339 --> 00:02:52.339
package as a way of providing general integration with Python from the R language, which Sean

00:02:52.339 --> 00:02:54.580
will be talking about in a moment.

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:59.619
And then most recently, over the last year or so, we've introduced a number of new capabilities

00:02:59.619 --> 00:03:09.059
around Python, including the support for Jupyter Notebooks and JupyterLab within our commercial

00:03:09.059 --> 00:03:13.380
products, which Sean will be talking about.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:22.619
So in talking to our customers and other data science teams out there, we've seen a lot

00:03:22.619 --> 00:03:27.339
of common challenges for these bilingual data science teams, a lot of the same problems

00:03:27.339 --> 00:03:29.419
that they struggle with.

00:03:29.419 --> 00:03:34.740
Data scientists, for example, are focused on using and finding the best tool for the

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:36.139
job.

00:03:36.139 --> 00:03:39.460
And when they're trying to use R and Python together, that means they often need to switch

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.940
context between these multiple different environments.

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:45.940
And they struggle with just the cognitive switching and doing that.

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:52.339
To support that switching, DevOps and IT have to spend time and resources to maintain and

00:03:52.339 --> 00:03:57.460
manage and scale these separate environments for R and Python in a cost effective way,

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:03.380
often struggling with that because they might not have the skills and the open source tools

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:06.580
that underlie both environments.

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:11.580
Data science leaders, the people who manage and really try and maximize the value and

00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:17.299
efficiency of these data science teams, wrestle with how to share results consistently and

00:04:17.299 --> 00:04:22.660
deliver value to the larger organization because ultimately the data science team is there

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:28.059
to provide insights so they can help the organization make better decisions.

00:04:28.059 --> 00:04:32.059
The data science leaders also want to focus on how do we provide the tools for collaboration

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:34.980
between these R and Python users?

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:39.820
Because if these users are siloed, then they might end up reinventing the same algorithms,

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:45.299
the same processes, the same analyses in these different environments and wasting time and

00:04:45.299 --> 00:04:48.700
effort doing that.

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:52.459
And then the business stakeholders are ultimately not interested typically in the underlying

00:04:52.459 --> 00:04:57.940
details in whether or not the data science products that they receive are based on R and

00:04:57.940 --> 00:04:58.940
Python.

00:04:59.019 --> 00:05:03.980
They just want to make sure that data science is credible and that they're able to leverage

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:07.980
those insights in order to make better decisions.

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:14.380
So these are the types of challenges that we've seen throughout many, many conversations

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:16.140
with different data science teams.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:22.700
And so we're very excited today to bring you a view into how we help solve those challenges.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:25.059
And with that, I'll hand it off to Sean.

00:05:25.059 --> 00:05:26.059
Awesome.

00:05:26.059 --> 00:05:28.220
Thank you so much, Lou.

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:30.459
And again, thanks everyone for joining.

00:05:30.459 --> 00:05:34.660
We're going to start by looking at some of the ways that a data scientist might combine

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:35.660
R and Python.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:40.299
And this is something that's near and dear to my heart because before joining RStudio,

00:05:40.299 --> 00:05:42.220
I sat exactly in this seat.

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:47.640
I was working with some really amazing engineers who were doing all of their stuff in Python.

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:51.859
I came from more of a stats background, so I was more comfortable with R. And I found

00:05:51.859 --> 00:05:58.179
myself spending a lot of time on pretty tedious tasks, running Python scripts, saving data

00:05:58.179 --> 00:06:03.779
to disk, loading it back up in R to make a plot, debugging when type conversions didn't

00:06:03.779 --> 00:06:07.500
work, just things that weren't very fun.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:12.700
And I'm excited today to show you, as a data scientist, how in RStudio with the open source

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:18.660
reticulate package, you can really work around a lot of that and very efficiently combine

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:19.660
these two languages together.

00:06:20.459 --> 00:06:23.339
So we're going to start with a couple of examples.

00:06:23.339 --> 00:06:30.100
So I'm going to switch over to RStudio and actually want to show you a shiny application.

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:34.839
And this is an application I inherited from that prior life.

00:06:34.839 --> 00:06:40.859
Basically what it allows someone to do is compare the fuel economy of two different

00:06:40.859 --> 00:06:47.260
vehicles going from point A to point B. And so maybe as an example, we could look at a

00:06:47.339 --> 00:06:52.059
Ford Explorer versus a Toyota Highlander hybrid.

00:06:52.059 --> 00:06:55.420
A simulation occurs behind the scenes here.

00:06:56.299 --> 00:06:58.140
And then we get the result.

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:02.779
In this case, the Ford Explorer uses more gas than the hybrid.

00:07:03.579 --> 00:07:09.980
So this is an interesting application because all of that simulation is occurring in Python.

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:19.019
In fact, the code that I inherited from my engineers is this really huge thousands of

00:07:19.019 --> 00:07:23.820
lines of Python code that handles the simulations here.

00:07:24.700 --> 00:07:30.220
And what we struggled with before the reticulate package was how to make this code accessible

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:31.179
to others.

00:07:31.179 --> 00:07:37.100
No one on our team had the skill to build out a full-fledged web application framework

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:38.140
in Python.

00:07:38.140 --> 00:07:42.619
And so what we would end up doing is taking requests from different stakeholders.

00:07:42.619 --> 00:07:46.859
We would run these functions manually, and then we would return the results.

00:07:46.859 --> 00:07:49.739
And it was a really time-intensive and laborious process.

00:07:50.459 --> 00:07:56.540
So when the reticulate package came out, I was excited to be able to build using the

00:07:56.540 --> 00:07:59.100
amazing tools available in R around Shiny.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:05.179
I was excited to build this type of application that would allow those stakeholders to run

00:08:05.179 --> 00:08:07.179
experiments interactively themselves.

00:08:08.140 --> 00:08:11.579
So I want to show you a little bit of the code just so you get a feel for what this

00:08:11.579 --> 00:08:12.059
looks like.

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:19.179
Inside of the application, we're using the reticulate package to source this Python file.

00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:24.540
And this Python file has a whole bunch of functions inside of it that do all the heavy

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:25.420
lifting.

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:28.380
You can see one of them here is a sim drive.

00:08:29.179 --> 00:08:35.340
And once you've sourced that file, all you have to do is call it, call that function

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:37.820
as if it were an R function.

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:39.099
You can see that call here.

00:08:40.219 --> 00:08:44.299
And the reticulate package takes care of all the dirty work for you.

00:08:44.299 --> 00:08:47.900
So you don't have to worry about managing a subprocess yourself.

00:08:47.900 --> 00:08:50.380
You don't have to deal with type conversions.

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:54.940
Our data frames on the R side are going to become those dictionaries that the Python

00:08:54.940 --> 00:08:55.900
function needs.

00:08:55.900 --> 00:09:00.619
And then the Python function is going to return results that are nicely handled back into

00:09:00.619 --> 00:09:01.820
a tidy data frame.

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:05.340
And so a lot of that heavy lifting is done for you.

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:12.059
And it becomes really seamless to get started calling that Python code from the R interface.

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:18.539
Now, when you're doing that type of work, combining R and Python together, it's not

00:09:18.539 --> 00:09:23.659
only enough to be able to do that seamlessly, but you also typically don't want to have

00:09:23.659 --> 00:09:24.780
to context switch.

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:29.900
And so that leads to the second thing I want to show you, which is that inside of RStudio,

00:09:30.619 --> 00:09:36.140
again, based on the open source work that we've done with the reticulate package, you're

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:39.179
able to interact with Python files directly.

00:09:39.179 --> 00:09:41.580
And so this is a pretty simple Python file.

00:09:42.299 --> 00:09:47.900
And what I can do inside of RStudio is execute the code kind of line by line.

00:09:47.900 --> 00:09:55.419
And in this case, we're using NumPy and matplotlib to create a bivariate distribution plot.

00:09:55.419 --> 00:09:59.340
You can see the matplotlib image shows up in the plots panel.

00:09:59.979 --> 00:10:03.260
Our Python code is being executed line by line in the console.

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:09.099
And we even get some of the really nice ergonomics that you would expect from an IDE, such as

00:10:09.099 --> 00:10:12.539
autocomplete in the Python context, as well as help.

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:18.539
And this is really exciting because if you are inheriting those Python files or gluing

00:10:18.539 --> 00:10:23.179
them together with R code, it can be really nice to be able to interact with the Python

00:10:23.179 --> 00:10:28.059
files in one place without having to switch contexts to a totally different editor or

00:10:28.059 --> 00:10:28.780
a different tool.

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:36.940
So RStudio, by no means, is going to be a full-fledged IDE for Python development at

00:10:36.940 --> 00:10:37.820
this time.

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:43.500
But in my experience as a data scientist working with both of the languages, it meets my needs

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:46.219
and has a lot of the things I'm looking for.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:50.299
So that's how you might interact with a Python file directly.

00:10:50.299 --> 00:10:54.780
There's one other integration that we built into the IDE to make working with R and Python

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:58.299
together pretty seamless, and that's through R Markdown.

00:10:59.020 --> 00:11:03.500
R Markdown, if you're not familiar with it and you're coming from the Python side of

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:07.979
the world, it's very similar in its goal to a Jupyter notebook.

00:11:09.179 --> 00:11:13.580
It allows you to do what we call literate programming, where you're going to combine

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:21.580
text and prose alongside the output of code, all in a single scientific notebook or

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:22.780
computational document.

00:11:23.739 --> 00:11:28.619
That's what R Markdown allows you to do, but it's a little bit of a misnomer, R Markdown,

00:11:28.619 --> 00:11:32.859
because you can actually use a whole bunch of different languages inside of an R Markdown

00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:33.340
document.

00:11:34.059 --> 00:11:37.739
Of course, as you might guess, we're talking about Python today, so what I'm going to show

00:11:37.739 --> 00:11:41.580
you is how you can use Python and R inside of this document.

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:47.260
And we'll start by inserting a Python code chunk, and then let's load some data from

00:11:47.260 --> 00:11:49.820
the Seaborn Python library.

00:11:51.659 --> 00:11:55.739
And specifically, we're going to look at our favorite iris dataset.

00:11:56.619 --> 00:12:03.500
You can see the IDE's autocomplete at work, helping me get these function calls right.

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:10.059
And then we're going to use some Pandas syntax to subset this dataset that we've loaded,

00:12:10.780 --> 00:12:15.580
and specifically, we're going to look at one species of iris

00:12:18.219 --> 00:12:19.739
called Cytosa.

00:12:20.780 --> 00:12:25.260
Actually, let's not overload our variable names here.

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:26.539
We'll call this Cytosa.

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:30.460
And we can execute this right inside of RStudio.

00:12:31.500 --> 00:12:35.900
In the Python context, we can double check that we got things right here.

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:41.979
And so, this does look like the iris dataset with the Cytosa species.

00:12:41.979 --> 00:12:43.419
So, we're looking good so far.

00:12:44.219 --> 00:12:49.580
What I want to show you, and where things get kind of magical and really exciting, is

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:55.979
that from our R code chunk, we can now access everything we're just doing in the Python

00:12:55.979 --> 00:12:56.539
environment.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:01.340
So, specifically, let's load the ggplot2 library.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:08.780
And we're going to take a look at plotting this dataset.

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:15.500
And the way this works is there's a special object in our environment called pi that gives

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:21.179
us access to the Python environment and all the variables or data that is in that environment.

00:13:21.179 --> 00:13:26.940
So, here we have pi $Cytosa is going to give us access to that Pandas data frame.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:31.179
And we can go ahead and plot it.

00:13:31.179 --> 00:13:35.900
We don't have to, from there, we can do everything as if we were in R.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:41.979
So, we'll just make a simple plot here.

00:13:43.739 --> 00:13:48.940
And what's really interesting about this is it allows us to use the languages for what

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:49.979
they're really good at.

00:13:49.979 --> 00:13:54.380
So, as an example here, we're using Pandas, which is a pretty powerful tool for data

00:13:54.380 --> 00:13:54.940
manipulation.

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:59.739
And then ggplot2, which is really excellent for visualization.

00:13:59.739 --> 00:14:01.659
And so, we can run this R code.

00:14:03.260 --> 00:14:06.219
And, of course, we get an error here.

00:14:07.260 --> 00:14:11.099
Let's maybe see if we can figure out what's going on with this error real quick.

00:14:11.659 --> 00:14:17.419
One of the things that's really nice is with that Python environment, I can actually use

00:14:17.419 --> 00:14:20.940
some of the IDEs features to explore what's going on.

00:14:21.099 --> 00:14:28.539
So, as an example, I can view the dataset that's in Python using the view command.

00:14:28.539 --> 00:14:31.260
And it looks like this is the dataset we saw.

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:34.219
It's the iris filtered down to the Cytosa species.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:37.020
And actually, I think I know what I did wrong.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:40.460
It looks like on the Python version of this dataset, we have underscores.

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:43.179
I used periods.

00:14:43.179 --> 00:14:48.380
So, if we replace those periods with underscores, there we go.

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:52.859
We get our nice ggplot2 of the relationship between length and width.

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:59.500
So, those are just a couple of ways that a data scientist can combine R and Python inside

00:14:59.500 --> 00:15:00.619
of RStudio.

00:15:00.619 --> 00:15:05.659
All of that is using the open source tools that's going to be available wherever you're

00:15:05.659 --> 00:15:06.940
running RStudio.

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:09.260
At the heart of it is that reticulate package.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:14.700
The reticulate package uses the Python and R C++ APIs.

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:16.780
So, the data conversions are pretty fast.

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:20.460
It does use a little bit more memory than if you were using a single language.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:24.780
But it allows you to take advantage of tools in each language.

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:28.619
So, you can use R for what it's really good at and Python for what it's really good at.

00:15:29.179 --> 00:15:34.059
And just to kind of recap what we saw there, there is a combination of R and Python in

00:15:34.059 --> 00:15:35.739
R Markdown that we just looked at.

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:40.859
We also saw at the very beginning how you can use Python functions and execute Python

00:15:40.859 --> 00:15:47.020
code in the context of R scripts or functions, which is really useful if you want to build

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:50.140
like a shiny app that pulls in Python code.

00:15:50.140 --> 00:15:55.419
And then you can also just edit and play with Python code directly in RStudio as the IDE.

00:15:56.619 --> 00:16:02.619
Now, that's really useful for a data scientist to glue these two languages together.

00:16:02.619 --> 00:16:07.900
But what we see is that often it's not just a data scientist who has to worry about R

00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:10.059
and Python and the combination of the two.

00:16:10.059 --> 00:16:15.340
Especially in organizations, there's another really important team that gets involved with

00:16:15.340 --> 00:16:16.539
these two languages.

00:16:16.539 --> 00:16:22.940
And that's the DevOps or IT administration group that is responsible for creating that

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:29.820
environment where data scientists can be productive and have access to data and collaborate with

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:30.380
one another.

00:16:31.340 --> 00:16:36.219
What we tend to see working with a lot of these organizations as they're adopting R

00:16:36.940 --> 00:16:43.179
is that it can be a challenge to create an infrastructure that meets the needs of all

00:16:43.179 --> 00:16:44.219
these different languages.

00:16:45.739 --> 00:16:50.940
And what happens in the worst case scenario is that data scientists will just continue

00:16:50.940 --> 00:16:54.619
doing work on their own desktops where they're most comfortable.

00:16:54.619 --> 00:16:56.859
And that becomes really hard to troubleshoot.

00:16:57.739 --> 00:17:02.380
We've talked to IT admins who have hundreds of tickets in their system along the lines

00:17:02.380 --> 00:17:08.140
of this version of a Python package isn't installing and so I can't share a notebook

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:08.859
with my colleague.

00:17:09.739 --> 00:17:16.459
And so what we're excited to show you is RStudio's professional products, RStudio Server

00:17:16.459 --> 00:17:19.979
and RStudio Connect, which together kind of make up RStudio Team.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:26.459
And these professional products allow the DevOps and IT group to provide that single

00:17:26.459 --> 00:17:31.180
infrastructure where data science teams can use R and Python together.

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:36.380
And they can do it in their favorite tools, whether that's RStudio or Jupyter without

00:17:36.380 --> 00:17:38.699
resorting back to their desktop.

00:17:38.699 --> 00:17:42.459
That makes it easier for them to collaborate and work together.

00:17:42.459 --> 00:17:50.219
But it also means that IT only has to configure, maintain, scale a single environment instead

00:17:50.219 --> 00:17:54.699
of dealing with different tools for different languages across different teams.

00:17:55.339 --> 00:17:56.859
So I want to show you what that looks like.

00:17:57.819 --> 00:18:03.180
I'm actually going back to RStudio and one of the things that those of you with really

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:08.939
astute eyes might have noticed is that I'm actually using RStudio inside of a web browser,

00:18:08.939 --> 00:18:13.420
which might be a little bit different, especially if you're used to using RStudio as a desktop

00:18:13.420 --> 00:18:14.060
application.

00:18:14.699 --> 00:18:20.380
The reason that you see RStudio presented in a web browser is because all the computation

00:18:20.380 --> 00:18:22.619
here is happening on a server.

00:18:22.619 --> 00:18:27.979
And what that means is that Lou, myself, and the other data scientists at RStudio are

00:18:27.979 --> 00:18:30.300
all working on a consistent platform.

00:18:30.300 --> 00:18:33.260
So it's easier for us to share work with one another.

00:18:33.260 --> 00:18:37.339
It's easier for us to get access to the production data that we use at RStudio.

00:18:37.979 --> 00:18:44.300
And kind of one of my favorite parts is that I have a single entry point for all the different

00:18:44.300 --> 00:18:46.619
types of projects that I work on.

00:18:46.619 --> 00:18:49.420
So this is the RStudio server homepage.

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:55.660
You can see the Shiny application, that project we were just in, is sitting idle now on the

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:56.380
server.

00:18:56.380 --> 00:19:01.420
I have a job that I kicked off a couple of hours ago that's kind of running in the background.

00:19:01.420 --> 00:19:05.180
I don't have to worry about desktop updates interfering with that job.

00:19:06.219 --> 00:19:11.660
And the kind of new thing that we wanted to showcase is that when you go to start a new

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:15.180
session on RStudio, you now get to select what editor you want.

00:19:15.819 --> 00:19:21.099
So, of course, you can choose the RStudio IDE, and RStudio server will run that for

00:19:21.099 --> 00:19:21.660
you.

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:26.060
But you can also pick between things like JupyterLab and the Jupyter Notebook.

00:19:26.939 --> 00:19:30.540
I'll select Jupyter Notebook, and we'll kick this off in a second.

00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:35.420
But before we do that, I also want to call out another choice that's really powerful,

00:19:35.420 --> 00:19:38.219
which is where you want the computation to actually run.

00:19:38.939 --> 00:19:45.260
So traditionally, you would normally run R and Python kind of on the same environment

00:19:45.260 --> 00:19:48.219
in the same location where RStudio server was running.

00:19:49.020 --> 00:19:54.219
But in one of our goals to make the server and this infrastructure more extensible and

00:19:54.219 --> 00:19:59.579
easier for IT, we've added the ability to offload some of that computation to other

00:19:59.579 --> 00:20:00.540
locations.

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:06.219
And so specifically what you're looking at here is an integration between RStudio server

00:20:06.219 --> 00:20:07.500
and a Kubernetes cluster.

00:20:08.619 --> 00:20:14.380
Our Kubernetes cluster happens to be running an AWS, but you can be running Kubernetes

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:17.500
on any of the cloud providers or even on premise yourself.

00:20:18.060 --> 00:20:22.619
And what this allows me to do as a data scientist is without learning any new tools or new work

00:20:22.619 --> 00:20:29.500
benches, right from within RStudio server, I can pick the profile of tasks that I'm going

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:29.900
to have.

00:20:29.900 --> 00:20:33.819
So what CPUs I need, the size of memory that I want.

00:20:33.819 --> 00:20:39.979
And then my IT group has put together a couple of images, Docker images that will control

00:20:39.979 --> 00:20:43.339
the environment where this Jupyter notebook is going to run.

00:20:44.540 --> 00:20:48.939
So this gives a lot of flexibility for our team to specify exactly what we're looking

00:20:48.939 --> 00:20:51.500
for while still scaling elastically.

00:20:51.500 --> 00:20:53.180
And that's all inside of RStudio.

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:56.699
We don't have to jump between different tools or different environments.

00:20:57.339 --> 00:21:03.579
And so if I start this session, you'll see on the homepage, the RStudio ID, as well as

00:21:03.579 --> 00:21:09.900
the Jupyter notebook, I can fire up this Jupyter notebook and it's going to give me

00:21:09.900 --> 00:21:14.780
the same files, the same access that I had from RStudio.

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:19.500
And so like any data scientist, I didn't do a great job cleaning up my workspace.

00:21:19.500 --> 00:21:25.579
I have a whole bunch of things going on here, but I can open up a specific set of examples

00:21:26.140 --> 00:21:27.180
that I created for today.

00:21:28.140 --> 00:21:31.979
All these examples in code are going to be online and we're happy to share them after

00:21:31.979 --> 00:21:32.859
the webinar.

00:21:32.859 --> 00:21:36.300
But I just want to show you what it looks like to run a Jupyter notebook here.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:43.099
And it actually might be a little bit of a letdown because what it looks like is a Jupyter

00:21:43.099 --> 00:21:43.579
notebook.

00:21:44.540 --> 00:21:48.939
You're able to execute the code chunks inside of Jupyter.

00:21:48.939 --> 00:21:50.540
You can see the results.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:55.979
And we've tried really hard at RStudio to give you as short a path as possible to the

00:21:55.979 --> 00:21:57.260
tool that you're comfortable with.

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:02.060
So we don't require a steep learning curve around anything else.

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:04.780
We just give you access to Jupyter right away.

00:22:05.979 --> 00:22:10.699
Inside of this notebook, though, we are still in that server side environment, which is

00:22:10.699 --> 00:22:17.660
really nice because it means that the Python kernels that we have are kind of shared and

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:20.300
can be shared amongst different data scientists.

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:24.939
So if you're onboarding someone new to Python, they're going to have access to that shared

00:22:24.939 --> 00:22:29.420
environment that your IT group has set up, in this case, that shared Docker image, so

00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:31.660
that we're all kind of playing from the same playbook.

00:22:32.300 --> 00:22:38.060
And while that's desirable a lot of the time, for advanced Python power users, you still

00:22:38.060 --> 00:22:42.219
have the ability to create your own kernels, set up your own virtual or con environments

00:22:42.219 --> 00:22:43.579
for specific projects.

00:22:43.579 --> 00:22:46.140
So all of that same tooling is available to you.

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:53.420
The only difference between this Jupyter notebook launch through RStudio server and a Jupyter

00:22:53.420 --> 00:22:57.579
notebook you might run yourself are two buttons that you'll see here.

00:22:57.660 --> 00:23:03.260
So one is this RStudio icon, and you can tell it really is a love story.

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:06.060
The two icons are even sitting next to each other.

00:23:06.060 --> 00:23:10.699
And this just takes you back, if you want, to your homepage, where you can see all the

00:23:10.699 --> 00:23:12.939
different projects and contexts that you're working on.

00:23:14.699 --> 00:23:19.900
Inside the Jupyter notebook, if we go back to that running notebook, the other icon that

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:24.219
you'll notice is this publish button, and we'll talk about that in just a second.

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:26.219
So remember that icon.

00:23:28.459 --> 00:23:34.140
So to summarize, for DevOps and IT, one of the things that's really critical when you

00:23:34.140 --> 00:23:39.579
have R and Python users is being able to provide them a consistent entry point that has their

00:23:39.579 --> 00:23:44.060
favorite tools without introducing a whole bunch of headaches and hurdles.

00:23:44.859 --> 00:23:47.420
And RStudio team is an easy way to do that.

00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:54.619
In a single product, only configured and integrated once, you're able to give folks access to

00:23:54.619 --> 00:23:59.500
the RStudio ID on the R side, which folks know and love, as well as their favorite tools

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:01.739
on the Python side, such as Jupyter notebooks.

00:24:02.380 --> 00:24:08.780
And we'll be extending that suite of editors as well, and that corresponds to an extension

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:10.140
in the number of backends, too.

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:14.459
So I showed you Kubernetes as one way to run and execute this content.

00:24:14.459 --> 00:24:20.540
There's also plugins if you want to run these different editors on more traditional HPC

00:24:20.540 --> 00:24:22.859
infrastructure that you might have at your organization.

00:24:24.619 --> 00:24:26.140
So we've covered data scientists.

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:28.300
We've covered IT and ops.

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:34.540
There's a third set of important folks that Lou mentioned at the beginning who care about

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:40.380
R and Python, and that's the data science team leaders or data science managers and

00:24:40.380 --> 00:24:42.780
ultimately the business stakeholders.

00:24:42.780 --> 00:24:48.859
And we combine these together on a single slide because we believe their concerns are

00:24:48.859 --> 00:24:53.020
largely two sides of the same coin.

00:24:53.099 --> 00:24:59.180
On the one hand, data science leaders, they're looking at how do I onboard new users into

00:24:59.180 --> 00:25:03.819
these different ecosystems where they can collaborate with the team without having to

00:25:03.819 --> 00:25:06.780
reinvent wheels or spend time doing translation.

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:13.099
I was talking to one manager at a pharmaceutical company, and they're trying to get more than

00:25:13.099 --> 00:25:16.459
500 SAS users into these open source tools.

00:25:16.459 --> 00:25:21.819
So it becomes really important that as you do those trainings and onboardings, it's a

00:25:21.819 --> 00:25:22.699
seamless process.

00:25:24.699 --> 00:25:29.099
Business stakeholders, meanwhile, they share some of the same goals of the data science

00:25:29.099 --> 00:25:29.420
leader.

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:33.020
They really want to see a return on their investment in the data science team.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:38.859
And ultimately what they care about more so than whether you use R and Python is just

00:25:38.859 --> 00:25:44.540
getting insights from the team so they can make good decisions and not rely only on their

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:45.099
intuition.

00:25:45.979 --> 00:25:49.979
And critical to doing that is their ability to interact with the team quickly.

00:25:50.619 --> 00:25:55.900
We want to avoid slow iteration times and emails back and forth asking for requests

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:57.900
between the different team members.

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:05.979
And so the last thing I'll kind of show you is how RStudio team in combination with R

00:26:05.979 --> 00:26:09.660
and Python allows you to address some of these challenges.

00:26:09.660 --> 00:26:13.819
And specifically, we're going to look at what it means to take some of those Python and

00:26:13.819 --> 00:26:19.579
R data products and put them into production on a tool that we call RStudio Connect.

00:26:20.540 --> 00:26:27.099
And so I'm going to switch back here to the Shiny application that we started the demo

00:26:27.099 --> 00:26:27.260
with.

00:26:28.780 --> 00:26:34.780
And this application, as we mentioned at the beginning, one of the things that's really

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:40.939
nice about a Shiny application is that it gives you the ability to allow stakeholders

00:26:40.939 --> 00:26:46.780
who may have specific domain expertise to play around with your code and run experiments.

00:26:46.780 --> 00:26:52.060
The challenge here is that right now this application is kind of trapped on my development

00:26:52.060 --> 00:26:52.939
environment.

00:26:52.939 --> 00:26:53.979
It's not easy to share.

00:26:54.619 --> 00:26:59.900
If I close out of RStudio, the application goes away.

00:26:59.900 --> 00:27:04.699
And so what we need to do is move it into production, into a place where others are

00:27:04.699 --> 00:27:06.619
going to be able to interact with it and rely on it.

00:27:07.180 --> 00:27:12.060
And in RStudio, it's easy to do that through that publish icon we were talking about.

00:27:12.780 --> 00:27:18.859
So all I have to do to deploy this to my production Connect server, which is a server that's

00:27:18.859 --> 00:27:24.060
running on premise, I'm not locked in to a platform as a service, I'm not sending my

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:30.780
data outside my firewall, I'm just deploying to another server with a production intent,

00:27:30.780 --> 00:27:32.060
is click publish.

00:27:32.060 --> 00:27:36.780
And what's going to happen is that the R and Python environments are going to be identified,

00:27:36.780 --> 00:27:41.900
all the different files and packages that are in use are going to be listed, and then

00:27:41.979 --> 00:27:46.780
sent to RStudio Connect, where that environment is going to be restored and the application

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:47.500
is going to be run.

00:27:48.459 --> 00:27:54.300
So I'll kind of, like those old cooking shows, this is the ingredients.

00:27:54.300 --> 00:27:59.180
And I'm going to jump to the end, pulling the final product out of the oven.

00:27:59.180 --> 00:28:04.540
But this is where the application will live and what it'll look like after it's deployed

00:28:04.540 --> 00:28:05.660
to RStudio Connect.

00:28:06.939 --> 00:28:09.819
And so the application here will load for us.

00:28:09.979 --> 00:28:14.619
That same application we've been playing with the whole time, but now it's in a production

00:28:14.619 --> 00:28:15.339
context.

00:28:15.339 --> 00:28:16.859
And so what does that mean?

00:28:16.859 --> 00:28:22.300
Well, very critically, it means that I have a stable URL I can share with stakeholders,

00:28:22.300 --> 00:28:27.500
and then they can go and access this dashboard and not even need to know that it was written

00:28:27.500 --> 00:28:28.619
in R or in Python.

00:28:28.619 --> 00:28:29.979
They don't need to know the details.

00:28:29.979 --> 00:28:31.579
It just becomes a web application.

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:36.140
I also have a lot of those things that IT is going to care about.

00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:42.619
So I can specify specific users so that this environment is secure and locked down to specific

00:28:42.619 --> 00:28:43.500
users or groups.

00:28:44.140 --> 00:28:50.300
I can look at the logs so I don't have to email someone in IT to try to download a log

00:28:50.300 --> 00:28:51.500
file and send it to me.

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:55.260
I can actually look at those and kind of iterate and debug in real time.

00:28:55.900 --> 00:28:58.859
And then also, very critically, I can scale.

00:28:58.859 --> 00:29:04.780
So we've used RStudio Connect to scale to more than 10,000 users at a single time.

00:29:04.780 --> 00:29:10.780
So 10,000 concurrent users looking at a dashboard that involves both R and Python.

00:29:10.780 --> 00:29:14.300
So it's really good at managing all of those processes and connections for you.

00:29:15.739 --> 00:29:21.819
So that's an example of a Shiny application that is going to allow business stakeholders

00:29:21.819 --> 00:29:26.060
to get value really quickly and to be able to iterate and run their own experiments.

00:29:26.060 --> 00:29:30.540
But dashboards and applications aren't the only thing that data science teams create.

00:29:31.339 --> 00:29:36.859
In fact, one of the things that we were talking about at the beginning was those Jupyter notebooks.

00:29:36.859 --> 00:29:39.979
And so you can publish Jupyter notebooks to RStudio Connect.

00:29:40.780 --> 00:29:44.540
And that becomes a really powerful way for teams to share their work.

00:29:44.540 --> 00:29:48.780
You can have a notebook that documents your experiment, your thinking,

00:29:48.780 --> 00:29:51.260
and that'll be available to everyone.

00:29:51.260 --> 00:29:55.180
And we have that support for Jupyter notebooks, but also for R Markdown.

00:29:55.180 --> 00:29:57.739
So it doesn't matter what language you're using.

00:29:57.739 --> 00:30:01.020
Your work can be shared in a single place that becomes

00:30:01.020 --> 00:30:04.060
a ground truth for the knowledge that the data science team has.

00:30:05.339 --> 00:30:08.459
The other thing that you can do with these notebooks that gets really powerful

00:30:08.459 --> 00:30:13.099
is once they're deployed to Connect, Connect can run them on a schedule.

00:30:13.099 --> 00:30:17.819
And so I actually want to show you an example of an R Markdown document.

00:30:17.819 --> 00:30:20.780
This document is scheduled to run twice a week.

00:30:21.339 --> 00:30:26.459
We can look at the historical versions of this document that have been published over time.

00:30:26.459 --> 00:30:30.219
But one of the things that's really interesting about this R Markdown document

00:30:30.219 --> 00:30:33.180
is that it's designed to communicate with stakeholders.

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:37.979
So essentially what it's doing is every twice a week on Mondays and Wednesdays,

00:30:37.979 --> 00:30:40.219
it checks inventory supplies.

00:30:40.219 --> 00:30:43.339
It runs a forecast and a burndown analysis.

00:30:43.339 --> 00:30:46.939
And then if there's a discrepancy between the inventory and the forecast,

00:30:47.500 --> 00:30:55.099
it actually uses code in RStudio Connect scheduler to send an email to stakeholders,

00:30:55.099 --> 00:30:57.020
in this case, the supply team.

00:30:57.020 --> 00:31:00.300
And that email is fully customized through the code.

00:31:00.300 --> 00:31:03.099
So you can include results, you can include plots.

00:31:03.979 --> 00:31:06.619
And those are going to show up in your stakeholders inbox

00:31:06.619 --> 00:31:08.619
so they can look at it right on their phone.

00:31:08.619 --> 00:31:14.300
And that's helpful in those cases where people want to get alerts or monitor something

00:31:14.300 --> 00:31:17.180
without having to constantly refer back to a dashboard.

00:31:17.819 --> 00:31:20.939
That's available for R Markdown documents that are, again,

00:31:20.939 --> 00:31:23.579
allowing you to combine Python and R together.

00:31:23.579 --> 00:31:27.420
So it's a powerful way to operationalize some of that work that the team is doing.

00:31:28.939 --> 00:31:33.739
But one other piece of content or pillar of content that I want to show you on Connect

00:31:34.459 --> 00:31:37.739
is how you might go about deploying a model.

00:31:37.739 --> 00:31:41.660
So often data science teams are responsible for creating models.

00:31:42.300 --> 00:31:45.739
And we've kind of seen how models could be shared with people

00:31:45.739 --> 00:31:49.099
in something like a dashboard or a notebook.

00:31:49.660 --> 00:31:53.260
But often you also need to share those models with other services.

00:31:53.260 --> 00:31:58.219
Maybe it's a website, maybe it's an application written in something like Java.

00:31:58.219 --> 00:32:03.819
But those tools want to consume the smart insights that you've created in R and Python.

00:32:03.819 --> 00:32:08.619
And the way that you can do that easily is by hosting your model as a RESTful API.

00:32:09.339 --> 00:32:12.859
So I just want to give you an example of what that looks like on RStudio Connect.

00:32:12.859 --> 00:32:17.500
The code for this API, so you can get a sense for what it looks like to actually write it,

00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:19.180
is something we'll share after the webinar.

00:32:20.140 --> 00:32:24.219
But in this case, our model is a sentiment predictor.

00:32:24.219 --> 00:32:29.260
So essentially, the model takes as an input a string,

00:32:29.260 --> 00:32:31.420
so maybe something like the word debugging.

00:32:32.140 --> 00:32:37.339
And we call this model on Connect using a RESTful request.

00:32:37.339 --> 00:32:38.540
It looks like this.

00:32:38.540 --> 00:32:41.420
So this is something a software engineer would be really familiar with.

00:32:42.219 --> 00:32:45.900
And then the model returns the sentiment,

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:52.300
zero being negative if the phrase was not very happy, or one being really positive.

00:32:52.300 --> 00:32:55.819
In this case, debugging is not very positive.

00:32:56.540 --> 00:32:59.900
If we send the model something like great beer,

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:07.900
turns out that great beer is quite a bit more positive, much closer to one.

00:33:09.099 --> 00:33:12.859
And so this model is using R, it's also using Python,

00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:17.579
a Python library called Spacey is actually what's giving us the sentiment scores.

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:22.060
And just like we saw with the application, the Shiny app,

00:33:22.060 --> 00:33:25.819
RStudio Connect is handling the access controls, the logs,

00:33:25.819 --> 00:33:28.939
scaling the number of processes to handle requests.

00:33:28.939 --> 00:33:33.900
So there's a lot of flexibility here as you operationalize these models.

00:33:36.219 --> 00:33:39.739
And so to kind of summarize, really what we're after

00:33:39.819 --> 00:33:43.900
is making it easier for people to make important decisions with data.

00:33:44.780 --> 00:33:48.859
And that's going to require teams to use R and Python together.

00:33:49.739 --> 00:33:53.260
And there are some considerations for team leaders and stakeholders

00:33:53.819 --> 00:33:55.260
when they set out to do that.

00:33:55.260 --> 00:33:59.260
The big ones are being able to access those insights consistently and reliably,

00:33:59.260 --> 00:34:01.339
which is really what production means.

00:34:01.339 --> 00:34:06.140
And for teams, it's being able to deliver that content regularly and seamlessly.

00:34:06.780 --> 00:34:12.300
And so that's what RStudio team and specifically RStudio Connect is designed to do,

00:34:12.300 --> 00:34:17.820
is to help those decision makers really rely on those data insights

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:20.219
and to ultimately get a return on the investment

00:34:20.219 --> 00:34:23.100
from the data scientists work in any language.

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:27.100
So with that, I'm going to hand things back over to Lou

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:31.020
to kind of recap what we've talked about and look ahead into the future a little bit.

00:34:33.419 --> 00:34:35.179
Thank you, Sean. I appreciate that.

00:34:35.179 --> 00:34:37.580
That was a great series of demos

00:34:37.580 --> 00:34:41.020
illustrating the way that we help our customers

00:34:41.020 --> 00:34:43.340
tackle the major challenges of bilingual teams.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:47.659
So just recapping what Sean just showed,

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:51.500
through our products, we allow data scientists

00:34:51.500 --> 00:34:55.500
to combine R and Python in a single project using the Reticulate package.

00:34:56.139 --> 00:34:59.659
We make it easy for these data scientists to launch Jupyter Notebooks

00:34:59.659 --> 00:35:04.300
or JupyterLab from the same infrastructure where they launch the RStudio IDE.

00:35:06.060 --> 00:35:08.139
From the DevOps and IT perspective,

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:13.340
we make it possible to provide all this capability in a single infrastructure

00:35:13.340 --> 00:35:15.659
for both R and Python and Jupyter,

00:35:16.780 --> 00:35:19.419
which means users can continue to use their favorite tools,

00:35:19.419 --> 00:35:22.540
whether it's the RStudio IDE or whether it's a Jupyter Notebook.

00:35:24.219 --> 00:35:26.860
And very importantly, from the DevOps perspective,

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:32.699
they're making their users happy while making their own lives simpler and less expensive

00:35:32.699 --> 00:35:35.659
by configuring and integrating and scaling and securing

00:35:35.659 --> 00:35:39.340
a development infrastructure just once as opposed to multiple times.

00:35:40.860 --> 00:35:42.620
From the data science leader's point of view,

00:35:43.419 --> 00:35:46.860
we've shown how it's easy now to collaborate across your team,

00:35:47.659 --> 00:35:50.379
sharing your R and Python work between those team members,

00:35:50.939 --> 00:35:52.459
maximizing their productivity,

00:35:53.260 --> 00:36:00.620
and how to really repeatably, reproducibly deliver value to the business

00:36:00.620 --> 00:36:07.260
by delivering regularly updated reports, custom results, and self-serve applications

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:12.219
through a single portal or directly in your stakeholders' inbox via email.

00:36:13.500 --> 00:36:15.500
And from the business stakeholders' point of view,

00:36:15.500 --> 00:36:19.260
it's possible for them to access all these up-to-date interactive analyses,

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:23.500
dashboards, and emails, making sure that these results are current

00:36:23.500 --> 00:36:25.580
since they can be updated on a scheduled basis,

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:29.739
and so that they can get the answers, the insights they need

00:36:29.739 --> 00:36:32.060
when they want them in order to make better decisions.

