00:45:07.340 --> 00:45:09.659
One is there's a series of questions

00:45:09.659 --> 00:45:13.820
that's along the lines of why should I learn Python?

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:14.860
One questioner asked,

00:45:14.860 --> 00:45:17.260
does the data scientist need to know all the languages?

00:45:18.139 --> 00:45:20.379
Another questioner asks, what's better in R?

00:45:20.379 --> 00:45:23.020
Another questioner asks, what's better in Python?

00:45:24.060 --> 00:45:27.340
And one questioner suggests that in R,

00:45:27.340 --> 00:45:30.780
ggplot and Shiny are particular strengths of R

00:45:30.780 --> 00:45:32.939
that Python users might want to leverage.

00:45:32.939 --> 00:45:33.899
So any thoughts there?

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:36.620
Yeah, those are great questions.

00:45:37.739 --> 00:45:40.699
I think what we've really come to appreciate

00:45:40.699 --> 00:45:44.780
is that kind of pitting R and Python against one another

00:45:45.659 --> 00:45:47.020
just isn't really practical.

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:49.419
Data scientists and data science teams,

00:45:49.979 --> 00:45:50.860
at the end of the day,

00:45:51.500 --> 00:45:53.580
people are coming from different backgrounds.

00:45:53.580 --> 00:45:55.500
Some have learned R, some have learned Python,

00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:56.459
some have learned both.

00:45:57.340 --> 00:46:00.860
And so really the conversation to have

00:46:00.860 --> 00:46:03.340
is how do you use R and Python together

00:46:03.899 --> 00:46:06.939
in that kind of love story idea

00:46:06.939 --> 00:46:09.500
as opposed to which language is best.

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:11.659
Both are going to be around for the long term.

00:46:12.699 --> 00:46:16.060
And it is really going to depend on kind of your context.

00:46:16.699 --> 00:46:20.219
There's a lot of domain-specific packages in both languages.

00:46:21.260 --> 00:46:24.219
So if you're working in the insurance industry

00:46:24.219 --> 00:46:25.659
versus in the finance industry,

00:46:25.659 --> 00:46:28.780
you might find yourself using different packages

00:46:28.780 --> 00:46:29.580
for different needs.

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:33.580
So I know that's a little bit of dodging the question.

00:46:33.580 --> 00:46:36.939
The key thing, I think, is to not get hung up on,

00:46:37.739 --> 00:46:41.100
should I only learn R or should I only learn Python?

00:46:41.100 --> 00:46:43.500
Really, both languages are going to be needed to succeed.

00:46:46.379 --> 00:46:47.100
Excellent, thank you.

