but you know you need to install some Python packages

00:49:09.020 --> 00:49:10.139
to get things to work,

00:49:10.139 --> 00:49:13.659
you can take a look at those create and install functions.

00:49:15.179 --> 00:49:17.340
So there's a lot of flexibility there.

00:49:17.340 --> 00:49:20.699
There's a reticulate cheat sheet available online

00:49:20.699 --> 00:49:23.020
that's going to walk through a lot of that stuff.

00:49:23.020 --> 00:49:25.260
And then the one tip I would give folks

00:49:25.260 --> 00:49:30.860
is that the PyDiscoverConfig,

00:49:30.860 --> 00:49:32.060
so this function here,

00:49:32.780 --> 00:49:35.260
it is really helpful in that it tells you

00:49:35.260 --> 00:49:39.340
kind of what a version of Python has been identified

00:49:39.979 --> 00:49:42.139
and is in use by the R session.

00:49:43.580 --> 00:49:44.620
Kind of looking ahead,

00:49:44.620 --> 00:49:46.219
one of the things we're really excited

00:49:46.219 --> 00:49:47.739
about working on this year

00:49:47.739 --> 00:49:50.699
is extending the support for reticulate

00:49:51.260 --> 00:49:52.699
so that you're able to do a bit more

00:49:52.699 --> 00:49:56.699
of that environment management from the RStudio IDE

00:49:56.699 --> 00:50:00.459
with a little bit of help interactively through the UI.

00:50:02.139 --> 00:50:04.060
So hopefully that answers some of the questions there.

00:50:05.020 --> 00:50:06.939
There's a question on,

00:50:09.739 --> 00:50:13.100
will this functionality be available in RStudio Cloud?

00:50:15.179 --> 00:50:16.780
Yeah, excellent question.

00:50:16.780 --> 00:50:19.419
So RStudio Cloud today

00:50:19.979 --> 00:50:23.260
does not have the Python environments installed,

00:50:23.979 --> 00:50:26.379
but if that's something that's interesting to you,

00:50:26.379 --> 00:50:30.459
we'd love to chat about what types of projects

00:50:30.459 --> 00:50:31.820
you're hoping to work on.

00:50:31.820 --> 00:50:33.739
For those that are completely unfamiliar,

00:50:34.300 --> 00:50:37.580
RStudio Cloud is an environment

00:50:38.219 --> 00:50:39.899
for kind of right now,

00:50:39.899 --> 00:50:41.500
specifically geared at teaching,

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:42.860
though it also can be useful

00:50:42.860 --> 00:50:44.620
for individual projects as well.

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:47.260
What it essentially is,

00:50:47.260 --> 00:50:50.300
is a version of RStudio that we run.

00:50:50.300 --> 00:50:53.659
So everything we were talking about today in the webinar

00:50:53.659 --> 00:50:55.659
was for teams that are maintaining

00:50:55.659 --> 00:50:57.340
their own infrastructure

00:50:57.340 --> 00:50:59.979
or running RStudio just locally on your desktop.

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:03.100
But if you're an educator

00:51:03.100 --> 00:51:06.060
and you want to teach students about R and Python,

00:51:06.060 --> 00:51:07.500
it can be really annoying

00:51:07.500 --> 00:51:10.379
to have to spend the whole first week of class

00:51:10.379 --> 00:51:12.379
just trying to get R and RStudio

00:51:12.379 --> 00:51:14.540
and Python and Jupyter all installed.

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:18.620
And so RStudio Cloud solves that problem for you

00:51:18.620 --> 00:51:21.979
as support for what we call different workspaces.

00:51:21.979 --> 00:51:23.340
So you can set up a class,

00:51:23.340 --> 00:51:25.260
invite students to that class,

00:51:25.260 --> 00:51:27.580
and then they have an RStudio environment

00:51:27.580 --> 00:51:29.340
that's configured and ready to go.

00:51:29.979 --> 00:51:32.139
So if you're interested in using Python

00:51:32.139 --> 00:51:34.620
in your courses alongside of R,

00:51:34.620 --> 00:51:35.659
we'd love to hear from you

00:51:35.659 --> 00:51:37.260
so that we can understand

00:51:37.260 --> 00:51:39.020
what your requirements around Python might be.

00:51:39.580 --> 00:51:41.659
Someone in the question box had called us out

00:51:41.659 --> 00:51:45.659
for having Python 2.7 in our environment,

00:51:45.659 --> 00:51:46.780
and you're absolutely right.

00:51:47.340 --> 00:51:49.100
Python 2 isn't supported anymore,

00:51:49.100 --> 00:51:51.500
but practically it's still all around.

00:51:51.500 --> 00:51:53.260
We'd love to get your feedback,

00:51:53.260 --> 00:51:54.939
especially from educators,

00:51:54.939 --> 00:51:56.379
on what you're hoping to teach

00:51:56.379 --> 00:51:57.500
and what that right environment

00:51:57.500 --> 00:51:58.860
might look like for you.

00:51:58.860 --> 00:52:02.300
We got a question from one of the listeners

00:52:02.300 --> 00:52:03.419
who would like to know

00:52:03.419 --> 00:52:05.340
where they can find more resources

00:52:05.340 --> 00:52:07.580
regarding use cases for data scientists

00:52:07.580 --> 00:52:09.340
or DevOps and IT admins.

00:52:10.780 --> 00:52:11.820
Perhaps you want to show

00:52:11.820 --> 00:52:13.820
solutions.rstudio.com real quick,

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:15.419
unless you've got another suggestion on that.

00:52:16.219 --> 00:52:17.419
Yeah, absolutely.

00:52:17.419 --> 00:52:18.860
So Lou had mentioned

00:52:18.860 --> 00:52:20.699
there's a lot of great resources

00:52:20.699 --> 00:52:21.899
as part of this webinar

00:52:21.899 --> 00:52:23.500
that we'll be sharing afterwards.

00:52:24.860 --> 00:52:27.820
One of the things I'll point you to

00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:30.139
is this site called RStudio Solutions.

00:52:30.139 --> 00:52:33.580
It's available just at solutions.rstudio.com.

00:52:33.580 --> 00:52:36.139
This is going to have a bunch of those examples

00:52:36.139 --> 00:52:37.739
for what workflows look like

00:52:38.300 --> 00:52:39.659
for data science teams.

00:52:39.659 --> 00:52:42.219
And this is based on our interactions

00:52:42.219 --> 00:52:46.060
with more than 1,000 commercial entities

00:52:46.060 --> 00:52:47.100
that are doing work,

00:52:47.899 --> 00:52:49.899
running both of these languages in production.

00:52:51.020 --> 00:52:53.179
And it's also going to give some pointers

00:52:53.179 --> 00:52:55.979
for the IT or DevOps side of the house

00:52:55.979 --> 00:52:57.419
who are trying to answer questions

00:52:57.580 --> 00:52:59.179
like what should our architecture look like?

00:52:59.899 --> 00:53:03.020
Should we be doing things in Kubernetes?

00:53:03.020 --> 00:53:04.939
Should we be doing things in the cloud?

00:53:04.939 --> 00:53:07.100
Should we be running things locally?

00:53:07.100 --> 00:53:09.659
So all those questions are answered here.

00:53:09.659 --> 00:53:10.300
And then of course,

00:53:10.300 --> 00:53:12.219
we're happy to talk with you as well.

00:53:12.780 --> 00:53:15.979
The slides include that link

00:53:15.979 --> 00:53:17.340
to set up a meeting

00:53:17.340 --> 00:53:18.699
if you want to bounce ideas

00:53:18.699 --> 00:53:20.219
off of anyone on our team.

00:53:20.219 --> 00:53:23.100
So we have a few questions

00:53:23.100 --> 00:53:25.179
around deploying Shiny apps

00:53:26.060 --> 00:53:28.459
onto Connect and how that works.

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:30.780
One asks whether or not

00:53:30.780 --> 00:53:31.820
it's able to utilize

00:53:31.820 --> 00:53:33.179
a cluster behind the scenes.

00:53:33.899 --> 00:53:34.780
Another asks,

00:53:35.500 --> 00:53:37.100
once it's published on Connect,

00:53:37.820 --> 00:53:39.500
who is going to continue management?

00:53:39.500 --> 00:53:40.780
How does it scale up

00:53:40.780 --> 00:53:42.060
for more users to access?

00:53:42.699 --> 00:53:43.739
And another one asks

00:53:43.739 --> 00:53:44.699
whether it's possible

00:53:44.699 --> 00:53:45.580
to make that available

00:53:45.580 --> 00:53:46.459
outside of Firewall.

00:53:48.060 --> 00:53:49.739
Yeah, awesome questions.

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:51.659
Really exciting to hear

00:53:51.659 --> 00:53:53.979
about people delivering

00:53:53.979 --> 00:53:55.820
those applications into production.

00:53:55.820 --> 00:53:58.300
It's certainly probably the top thing

00:53:58.300 --> 00:54:00.620
that our customers are working on

00:54:00.620 --> 00:54:02.860
is how to get Shiny applications

00:54:02.860 --> 00:54:03.820
off of your laptop

00:54:03.820 --> 00:54:05.260
or your development environment

00:54:05.260 --> 00:54:06.699
into somewhere that's more stable.

00:54:07.659 --> 00:54:09.739
We can answer those questions

00:54:09.739 --> 00:54:11.820
specifically if folks have them.

00:54:12.540 --> 00:54:13.899
What I'll show you here,

00:54:13.899 --> 00:54:15.820
Connect is basically a product

00:54:15.820 --> 00:54:17.100
that runs on a server.

00:54:17.100 --> 00:54:18.699
It scales horizontally.

00:54:18.699 --> 00:54:20.620
So if you are concerned

00:54:20.620 --> 00:54:21.979
about having more people

00:54:21.979 --> 00:54:23.179
visiting your application

00:54:23.179 --> 00:54:25.340
than a single server can handle,

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:26.939
you can add multiple servers

00:54:26.939 --> 00:54:27.580
just like you would

00:54:27.580 --> 00:54:29.260
with any other web application

00:54:29.260 --> 00:54:31.100
and place them behind a load balancer.

00:54:32.139 --> 00:54:34.459
The deployment happens

00:54:34.459 --> 00:54:35.820
in a variety of ways.

00:54:35.820 --> 00:54:37.500
I showed you push button publishing.

00:54:38.379 --> 00:54:39.739
RStudio Connect also knows

00:54:39.739 --> 00:54:41.340
how to integrate with Git.

00:54:41.340 --> 00:54:42.620
So if you want to have

00:54:42.620 --> 00:54:44.300
a more Git-centric workflow,

00:54:44.300 --> 00:54:45.020
you can do that.

00:54:45.659 --> 00:54:47.899
Once the content is deployed,

00:54:47.899 --> 00:54:49.899
there's a lot that happens

00:54:49.899 --> 00:54:51.020
to help you manage

00:54:51.020 --> 00:54:52.780
kind of the ongoing life cycle

00:54:52.780 --> 00:54:54.139
of that content.

00:54:54.139 --> 00:54:55.020
So we mentioned that

00:54:55.020 --> 00:54:56.379
you can look at the logs.

00:54:57.179 --> 00:54:59.100
We talked about some of those

00:54:59.100 --> 00:55:01.419
scaling settings that'll help

00:55:01.419 --> 00:55:02.459
as you go to do that type

00:55:02.459 --> 00:55:03.659
of horizontal scaling.

00:55:04.540 --> 00:55:06.139
And then there's also things

00:55:06.139 --> 00:55:08.459
like default source versions,

00:55:08.459 --> 00:55:09.739
the ability to roll back

00:55:09.739 --> 00:55:11.100
and forwards in time.

00:55:11.100 --> 00:55:13.500
So there's just a lot of options there.

00:55:14.139 --> 00:55:15.500
At the end of the day,

00:55:15.500 --> 00:55:17.260
our goal, what we're trying to do

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:18.699
is help bridge that gap

00:55:18.699 --> 00:55:19.659
that often exists

00:55:19.659 --> 00:55:20.780
between data scientists

00:55:20.780 --> 00:55:21.820
who are creating

00:55:21.820 --> 00:55:23.580
these amazing applications

00:55:23.580 --> 00:55:25.659
and then IT operations

00:55:25.659 --> 00:55:28.139
who know a ton about servers

00:55:28.139 --> 00:55:29.739
and about best practices

00:55:29.739 --> 00:55:30.300
around things like

00:55:30.300 --> 00:55:31.580
infrastructure as code,

00:55:31.580 --> 00:55:33.260
but might be less familiar

00:55:33.260 --> 00:55:34.459
with R and Python.

00:55:35.100 --> 00:55:36.459
And so RStudio Connect

00:55:36.459 --> 00:55:37.580
acts as that bridge

00:55:38.620 --> 00:55:40.379
to serve a really nice balance

00:55:40.379 --> 00:55:41.340
where data scientists

00:55:41.340 --> 00:55:42.939
don't have to learn

00:55:42.939 --> 00:55:44.139
the gory details

00:55:44.139 --> 00:55:45.820
of server management

00:55:45.820 --> 00:55:47.020
and IT ops doesn't have

00:55:47.020 --> 00:55:48.139
to learn the gory details

00:55:48.139 --> 00:55:49.899
of things like R packages.

00:55:50.780 --> 00:55:52.300
The two can kind of meet

00:55:52.300 --> 00:55:53.820
and still have that robust

00:55:53.820 --> 00:55:56.060
and reliable production-ready service.

00:55:57.340 --> 00:55:58.459
Well, on that note,

00:55:59.419 --> 00:56:01.260
we are just about out of time.

00:56:01.899 --> 00:56:03.739
Sean and I and the rest of folks

00:56:03.739 --> 00:56:04.780
at RStudio would like

00:56:04.780 --> 00:56:05.580
to thank you again

00:56:05.580 --> 00:56:06.780
for attending this webinar.

00:56:07.340 --> 00:56:08.620
We were very excited

00:56:08.620 --> 00:56:10.060
to share all the work

00:56:10.060 --> 00:56:10.699
we've been doing

00:56:10.699 --> 00:56:11.979
around R and Python

00:56:11.979 --> 00:56:13.100
and how we help support

00:56:13.100 --> 00:56:14.780
bilingual data science teams

00:56:14.780 --> 00:56:16.379
in scaling out their data science

00:56:16.379 --> 00:56:17.419
across their organization.

00:56:19.899 --> 00:56:21.280
Thank you.

